source_code.code:
private void rehash() {
		int length = elementData.length<<1;
		if (length == 0) length = 1;
		firstSlot = length;
		lastSlot = -1;
		HashMapEntry[] newData = new HashMapEntry[length];
		for (int i=elementData.length; --i >= 0;) {
			HashMapEntry entry = elementData[i];
			while (entry != null) {
				int index = (hashCode(entry.key) & 0x7FFFFFFF) 
% length;
				if(index < firstSlot) firstSlot = index;
				if(index > lastSlot) lastSlot = index;
				HashMapEntry next = entry.next;
				entry.next = newData[index];
				newData[index] = entry;
				entry = next;
			}
		}
		elementData = newData;
		computeMaxSize();
	}

Bug.WithStack:
build I20030115

While stepping through code iterating over an array, I wanted to see a field 
of one of the elements while iterating, so I expanded the loop variable for 
the element.  However, every time I looped around, the variable for the 
element went out of scope, and the next time it entered the scope, it was 
collapsed.  I had to expand it each time.

The code in question is:

	private void rehash() {
		int length = elementData.length<<1;
		if (length == 0) length = 1;
		firstSlot = length;
		lastSlot = -1;
		HashMapEntry[] newData = new HashMapEntry[length];
		for (int i=elementData.length; --i >= 0;) {
			HashMapEntry entry = elementData[i];
			while (entry != null) {
				int index = (hashCode(entry.key) & 0x7FFFFFFF) 
% length;
				if(index < firstSlot) firstSlot = index;
				if(index > lastSlot) lastSlot = index;
				HashMapEntry next = entry.next;
				entry.next = newData[index];
				newData[index] = entry;
				entry = next;
			}
		}
		elementData = newData;
		computeMaxSize();
	}  

The loop variable "entry" is the one going in and out of scope.

Actually, I was really interested in a field (called fId) of the current key 
(instance TestElement in the JFace tests).
So I wanted both the expansion of "entry" to be remembered, and the expansion 
of "entry.key".

Basically, I think it would be a great advantage if it remembered all expanded 
paths in terms of variable and field names, e.g. {"entry", "key"}, rather than 
in terms of actual JDI variable and field references, so that when the JDI 
refs go out of scope, the expansion state still gets remembered.

It would be best if it remembered this per-frame, so if I stepped into another 
method then back out, I wouldn't lose the expansion state.  But I could live 
with it if it was just for the current frame.
Consider post 2.1
Consider for 3.0
Deferred
As of now 'LATER' and 'REMIND' resolutions are no longer supported.
Please reopen this bug if it is still valid for you.

