Bug.WithStack:
20030121
class A {
	int g;
	
	boolean blue;
	
//	public boolean isBlue() {
//		return blue;
//	}
//
//	public int getG() {
//		return g;
//	}
//
//	public void setBlue(boolean blue) {
//		this.blue = blue;
//	}
//
//	public void setG(int g) {
//		this.g = g;
//	}
//
}

calling delete (programatically or pressing del (same code)) on 'blue'
wipes out all the code that is commented out and leaves you with:

class A {
	int g;
	
}
I guess the source range is incorrect.
In fact this is the way the source range is computed for a DOMNode. The end of a
node is the end - 1 of its enclosing node if there is no next sibling. This is
your case here.
Changing this can lead to a problem because the comment contents won't be part
of any DOM node which is against the way they are specified. They need to cover
the whole unit.
I don't know if we want to change this that late in the game.
Current behavior seems useless. I would vote to improve for 2.1 (if doable).
Changing this can have an impact on all end positions. We might want to defer
the resolution of this PR when we will use DOM/AST for all operations.
Ok by me. Too dangerous for 2.1
Defer
As of now 'LATER' and 'REMIND' resolutions are no longer supported.
Please reopen this bug if it is still valid for you.

